<dl id="n54127e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54127e">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54127e"> 127(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> acid &amp; alkali = salt ~ <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54127e"><li>FW 167.19 </li><li><a href="../../flex/fd/lexfd.htm#n54127e">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/fd/l39fd.htm#n54127e">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54127e">MS BL 47476a-244</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:505 <a name=""fad8" href="../../FF/fdra/fda.htm#"fad8">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/fd/fdd7.htm#n54127e">Draft: I.6&sect;4.7</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Acids, Alkalis, and Salts. <p>From this experiment you learn&mdash; <br>1. That a substance is called an acid when it is sour and corrosive, and when it turns blue litmus solution red. <br>2. That an alkali is a substance which turns red litmus solution blue, and has the power of neutralizing acids. <br>3. That a <mark>salt</mark> is the substance formed when <mark>an acid combines with an alkali</mark> and forms a neutral body.</p> <small> H. E. Roscoe, <a name="HERC1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#HERC1"><cite title="source">Science Primer: Chemistry</cite></a> (n.d.) 81</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Acids and alkalis combine to form salts. </mm> </dd></dl>
